  <a name="planning"></a>
  <h1>Planning</h1>

  <h2> Rituals </h2>

  <p>
    <strong>Establishing Rituals</strong> was key to this project's success.
    With a gap in solution quality, I kicked off several rituals to enable
    feedback, collaboration, innovation, alignment, and big picture thinking.
  </p>

  <ul>
    <li>Bi-weekly Design critiques for feedback and quality.</li>
    <li>Weekly Design studio time for cross-functional collaboration.</li>
    <li>Weekly Design calibration for design quality calibration.</li>
    <li>Quarterly vision sprints for cross-functional future thinking.</li>
  </ul>

  <h2> Design Quality </h2>

  <p>
    I also improved the design function's ability
    <strong>to use data and research</strong> to inform design decisions. I took
    2 steps: First, I helped designers build relationships with Data Scientists
    by asking them to pair between projects and work together on assumptions.
    Second, I built more design rigor into our A/B testing processes, focusing
    on isolating design variables and designing with intent to learn.
  </p>

  <h2> Inclusive Planning </h2>

  <p>
    Finally, to bring divergent ideas and creativity to the project, I pitched
    an <strong>inclusive planning process.</strong> Working with
    cross-functional leads, we combined top-down and bottom-up approaches. We
    landed on the "W" approach: Leads established foundational direction, squads
    contributed feedback, and we iterated until we had a high-level plan for the
    year.
  </p>

  <a name="designing"></a>
  <h1>Designing</h1>

  <h2>Starting Smart </h2>

  <p>
    As a director, my role was to ensure team buy-in, define the exploration
    space, vet the direction, and define the best path forward to a solution. I
    de-risked our time investment by ensuring we aligned on the most important
    problem we felt was most easily solved.
  </p>

  <p>
    The first problem we would tackle was
    <strong
      >customers aren't discovering value outside of file, sync and
      share.</strong
    >
  </p>

  <p>
    The problem was large, but we felt solvable. To shorted the learning and
    exploration cycle. So I used the Google Venture Design Sprint, which
    emphasizes effective problem identification and iterative testing. I guided
    a Designer and Product Manager to run a Design Sprint with a team of 2
    designers, 2 product managers, 1 data scientist, 1 content designer, 1
    researcher, and 2 engineers.
  </p>

  <div class="work-image-container">
    <figure class="work-image">
      <%= image_tag "works/dropbox-activation-design-sprint.png" %>
      <figcaption>
        The 5-day Design Sprint Process created by Jake Knapp at Google
        Ventures.
      </figcaption>
    </figure>
  </div>

  <h2>
    The Design Sprint
  </h2>

  <p>
    <strong>On day one,</strong> the team and leadership had many assumptions to
    challenge: people struggle to find value due to a cluttered product, FSS is
    the only value, other features are neglected, and users lack usage
    knowledge. Using initial assumptions, research and behavioral data, the team
    identified a specific assumption to test: that relevant communication
    enhances feature and product discovery effectiveness.
  </p>

  <p>
    <strong>As the team diverged and converged,</strong> I participated in
    crazy-8s. One interesting idea was a bot named "Friend Lee" on Dropbox,
    acting as a fake teammate who learns from your actions and guides you. By
    day two, they selected two solutions to test their relevance assumption.
  </p>

  <p>
    <strong>On prototype day,</strong> the team built their ideas in Figma. The
    skilled designers crafted two polished experiences. One was a quiz-based
    onboarding process that gathered customer insights while providing valuable
    feedback. The other was a pattern triggered by actions, leading to a
    workflow chain.
  </p>

  <p>
    <strong>Finally, we tested the solutions.</strong> We tested the prototypes
    with 12 customers in one day. The two designers and researchers conducted
    two distinct tests with six users each. Everyone participated and took
    notes. The outcome showed that relevance was key. Smart suggestions that
    followed actions were effective, and customers were willing to share
    information if they understood it would guide them to specific actions.
  </p>

  <a name="experiments"></a>
  <h1>Experiments</h1>

  <h2>The Outcome</h2>

  <p>
    <strong>The sprint was a success.</strong> The team validated their
    assumption: "Feature and product discovery communication is effective when
    relevant." From here, we planned a series of experiments based on this
    learning.
  </p>

  <p>
    <strong>After the design sprint, we explored new ways to communicate with
    customers, discovered new engagement opportunities, and found different
    ways to understand their needs.</strong>
    Post-sprint, we conducted 12 experiments focused on connecting customers to
    Dropbox's full value. We continue to iterate with A/B tests and learning
    experiments.
  </p>

  <div class="work-image-container">
    <figure class="work-image">
