  <a name="challenges"></a>
  <h1>Internal Challenges</h1>

  <p>
    <strong
      >Different teams had goals that incentivized them to get as much traffic
      as possible to show gains.</strong
    >
    This created internal competition for customer attention. To solve this, I
    drafted an engagement model that focused on empowering experimentation while
    maintaining a high quality bar for shipping to a general audience. It
    specified criteria for exiting each stage and, most importantly, a process
    for escalation. My product partner Frances took this and ran with it,
    instilling this process across our org.
  </p>

  <div class="work-image-container">
    <figure class="work-image">
      <%= image_tag "works/dropbox-activation-working-model.png" %>
      <figcaption>
        The Dropbox Core Working Model created to improve outcomes through
        aligning incentives.
      </figcaption>
    </figure>
  </div>

  <p>
    <strong>We also struggled with a bad user experience.</strong> The varied
    ways teams got traffic resulted in what was called a "billboard" experience.
    Customers got peppered with upsells to different products or blocking
    recommendations to new features. To solve this, I created the CCC framework:
    Customer, Context and Content focused on quality over quantity. We tasked 1
    team to create an internal case study to prove the CCC framework's
    effectiveness.
  </p>

  <h2>The Case Study</h2>

  <p>
    <strong>Experiment A</strong>: A page takeover modal when customers
    landed, asking them to "Try DropboxSign." Of 10K people who saw it, 2.7%
    clicked, and 15 trials started. A 0.15% success rate.
  </p>

  <p>
    <strong>Experiment B</strong>: A rich confirmation appearing when
    customers upload a PDF (context) because we suspected they needed signing
    capabilities based on the filename (customer). Of 2K people who saw it, 5%
    clicked, 80 trials converted. 3.6% success rate. Roughly 300% better.
  </p>

  <div class="work-image-container">
    <figure class="work-image">
      <%= image_tag "works/dropbox-activation-bad-ux-before.png" %>
      <figcaption>
        Before: a page takeover often used to get clicks. It blocked users and
        was very ineffective.
      </figcaption>
    </figure>
  </div>

  <div class="work-image-container">
    <figure class="work-image">
      <%= image_tag "works/dropbox-activation-bad-ux-after.png" %>
      <figcaption>
        After: A "rich confirmation" popping up after a user takes an action.
        The confirmation is non-blocking, happens in response to an action, and
        guides the user to a connecting action.
      </figcaption>
    </figure>
  </div>

  <p>
    With teams collaborating and guidance on design strategy, we tackled
    <strong>an inconsistent UI.</strong> There was no source of truth for how
    activation experiences should be designed or how interfaces should look.
    This resulted in many disparate experiences and interfaces. I tasked a
    design manager to build a component library and partnered with them to
    evangelize it.
  </p>

  <div class="work-image-container">
    <figure class="work-image">
      <%= image_tag "works/dropbox-activation-inconsistent-ui.png" %>
      <figcaption>
        How the component collection was presented: name, description, visual,
