  <a name="learnings"></a>
  <h1>Learnings</h1>

  <p>
    Our biggest learning was that
    <strong>a one-size-fits-all approach doesn't scale.</strong> As product
    offerings grow, the audience becomes more complex, and their jobs-to-be-done
    expand. A combination of general activation (weak customer behavioral data)
    and targeted activation (strong customer behavioral data) is an effective
    way to scale activation experiences as products grow.
  </p>

  <p>
    But shipping at scale only works if the org is set up for it. We learned
    that <strong>goals drive outcomes more than principles.</strong> Misaligned
    goals can drive bad outcomes regardless of intention. If goals are
    misaligned, there's a high risk that one team's work can negatively impact
    another's.
  </p>

  <p>
    Finally, we learned that <strong>time constraints are our friends.</strong>
    When we forced time constraints, our rigor went up and scope went down.
    Speed became a valuable constraint to keep us from over-investing in
    unvalidated ideas. This shaped <%= link_to raw("one of my leadership values:
    to encourage deadlines."), values_path(anchor: 'encourage-deadlines') %>
  </p>

